intro: Fraxinus humilis, commonly known as the western wood maple, is a deciduous tree native to the western United States. It typically grows to a height of 10–20 feet and has a rounded, spreading crown. The leaves are opposite, ovate, and have three to five shallow lobes, turning yellow in the fall. Its small, winged samaras are produced in clusters and disperse by wind. The bark is smooth and grayish-brown, becoming fissured with age.
